    <name>
      <text>17.1.1.13 Classifying conic sections</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[Classify each of the following conics as circle, ellipse, parabola or hyperbola:

<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>{@poly[1]@} : [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</li>
<li>{@poly[2]@} : [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</li>
<li>{@poly[3]@} : [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]][[feedback:prt3]]</li>
<li>{@poly[4]@} : [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]][[feedback:prt4]]</li>
</ol>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[Recall that for a conic of the form
\[Ax^2+Bxy+Cy^2+Dx+Ey+F =0\]
<p>if not all of \(A,B,C\) are zero, the graph of the equation is:</p>
<ol type="i">
<li>an ellipse if \(B^2<4AC\) (circle if \(A = C\) and \(B=0\));</li>
<li>a parabola if \(B^2=4AC\);</li>
<li> an hyperbola if \(B^2>4AC\).</li>
</ol>
For our equations, calculating this we see:
<ol type="a">
<li>{@poly[1]@} is a {@first(mcq_correct(ta[1]))@} </li>
<li>{@poly[2]@} is a {@first(mcq_correct(ta[2]))@}</li>
<li>{@poly[3]@} is a {@first(mcq_correct(ta[3]))@} </li>
<li>{@poly[4]@} is a {@first(mcq_correct(ta[4]))@} </li>
</ol>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
